@given(st.integers()) def test_roundtrip(n): assert decode(encode(n)) == n. Hypothesis generates inputs, finds the smallest failing case, and remembers it across runs.

Why: example-based tests cover the cases you thought of. Property tests cover the cases you didn't. Off-by-one, boundary conditions, unicode oddities — found in seconds, not months.

When: pure functions with a clean invariant (encoders/decoders, parsers, transformations). Less useful for IO-heavy code where the cost is in the side effects.

@model_validator(mode='after') def end_after_start(self): if self.end < self.start: raise ValueError('end must be ≥ start'); return self. Runs after individual field validation, sees fully-typed fields.

Why: cross-field rules in @field_validator are awkward — you only see one field at a time. mode='after' is the v2 idiom and produces clean Pydantic error output that maps to the field path.

When: any constraint that spans two or more fields (date ranges, mutually-exclusive options, sum-to-100 percentages).
